# a.out ("assembler output") goes back to the very first unix on the pdp-7 /
# pdp-11 around 1969-1971. ken thompson's original assembler `as` wrote its
# output to a fixed filename `a.out` when no `-o` was specified, same as how
# `cc` later defaulted to it. the name stuck even though the assembler was
# quickly joined by a c compiler, a linker (`ld`), and others; all of them
# inherited the same default output name.


# the format

# the on-disk format also got the name a.out. early unix executables were a
# simple header + text + data + symbol table layout, described in
# /usr/include/a.out.h. the format evolved through several variants:
#
# - pdp-11 a.out
# - 32-bit vax / bsd a.out with ZMAGIC / NMAGIC / OMAGIC variants for
#   demand paging


# where it lived

# - research unix and early bsd into the 1980s
# - sunos 3.x
# - linux (until ~1995, kernel 1.2)
# - 386bsd / early netbsd / freebsd


# what replaced it

# - coff (system v)
# - elf (svr4, ~1988) — eventually adopted by linux (mid-90s) and the bsds
#   over the following years
# - mach-o on macos is a separate lineage from nextstep


# today

# 1. still the default output filename of cc / gcc / clang when you omit -o
#    — a 55-year-old default no one bothered to change
# 2. historical executable format, still readable by `file` and `binutils`,
#    but essentially extinct in production


# trivia

# - gnu ld will still happily produce a.out-format binaries if you ask it to
# - the linux kernel kept (deprecated) a.out loader support until it was
#   removed in 5.1 (2019)
